<FIRST>r a AM-ChippewaDeal     01-15 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chippewa Deal,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chippewa Indians Reject State Treaty Rights Buyout Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLE LAKE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a band of Chippewa Indians on
Saturday voted against a state proposal for a $10 million buyout to
limit the band's hunting and fishing treaty rights.
   Arlyn Ackley, tribal chairman, said the vote was 131-24 against
the proposal.
   The vote ``settles it for right now,'' Ackley said. ``There might
be another vote on it. We don't know yet.''
   The proposal made by the state called for paying $1.25 million
the first year and $1 million a year for the next nine years, he
said. In exchange, the band would give up treaty spearfishing
rights, except for certain ceremonial purposes, and lumbering rights
on non-reservation public lands.
   Seventy-five percent of the money would have been earmarked for
economic development projects. The remainder would have gone to
tribal administration and health and welfare programs.
   The proposal did not allow splitting the money between the band's
1,093 members, many of whom live off the reservation in northern
Wisconsin.
   Ackley said news media descriptions of the proposal may have
prevented members of the Mole Lake, or Sokaogon, band from
understanding the deal as a lease agreement, not ``a buyout or
sellout.''
   ``More people were interested in not selling their
rights...That's what people (thought they) were voting on, whether
they were selling their rights or not,'' said Ackley.
   ``It could have been a 25-year lease agreement,'' if extended
beyond the initial 10 years, he said.
   It was the first settlement proposal to be made by the state to
one of Wisconsin's six Chippewa bands. The Mole Lake band is the
smallest of the six.
   At issue are the rights upheld in federal court rulings for the
Chippewa to fish, hunt and gather wild grain from non-reservation
lands ceded to the U.S. government under 19th century treaties.
 
</TEXT>
