<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Yabuta     01-15 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Yabuta,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Japanese To Receive Liver Transplant Overseas Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hiroshi Yabuta, the first Japanese to receive a
liver transplant in another country, has died, a hospital official
said Sunday. He was 53.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Yabuta
died Friday of acute kidney failure at Kinki University Hospital in
western Japan.
   No liver or heart transplants have been performed in Japan since
1968 because of controversy over the legal definition of death for
potential organ donors. Yabuta received the transplant at
Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston on April 8, 1985, and
returned home seven months later.
   In 1968, an 18-year-old boy underwent Japan's first heart
transplant but died 82 days later at Sapporo Medical College in
northern Japan.
   The doctor who performed the operation was accused of obtaining
the heart from a brain-dead person. Traditionally, Japanese have
considered death to occur only after a person's heart stops beating.
   The doctor was accused of murder in a citizen's complaint, but
official murder charges were never filed.
   Nevertheless, Japanese doctors halted heart and liver transplants
as a result of the controversy.
   The hospital official refused to provide further details on
Yabuta's death, but Kyodo News Service said an autopsy showed no
irregularities in Yabuta's transplanted liver or any symptoms of
rejection.
   It said his death may have been caused by a decline in body
resistance caused by medicine Yabuta took to prevent rejection of
the liver.
   Since Yabuta's transplant about 30 Japanese, mostly children,
have received liver transplants in the United States, Europe and
Australia. Eight of them have died, Kyodo said.
</TEXT>
