<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--LoggingBan     01-15 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Logging Ban,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Signs Ban On Logging After Devastating Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The king has approved a ban on logging,
which was blamed for causing floods that killed more than 350
people, a newspaper reported Sunday.
   King Bhumibol Adulyadej signed decrees Saturday that empowered
the agriculture minister to revoke 301 logging concessions in 4.8
million acres that straddle national parks and wildlife conservation
areas, The Nation said.
   The decrees, approved by the Cabinet on Tuesday, are expected to
be passed by Parliament when it opens in May.
   ``We have almost no forests left,'' the newspaper quoted Prime
Minister Chatichai Choonhavan as saying. ``The principle is that we
have to protect the remaining forests.''
   In the November floods, people were killed as mud, felled logs
and trees rolled down barren hillsides and buried villages.
   The prime minister said Thailand would import logs and wood
products from Malaysia, Burma, Laos and Indonesia.
</TEXT>
