<FIRST>r i AM-China-Africans     01-15 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Africans,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expelled African Says He Was Beaten By Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An African student who was jailed and ordered to
leave China for a fight that touched off racial demonstrations said
Sunday police had beaten him and shocked him with electric prods.
   Dossoumou Boni Lodovic arrived in Beijing a day after police in
Nanking released him from two weeks of solitary confinement. Chinese
authorities have given him until Tuesday to leave the country.
   ``I'm happy as anything to be leaving China,'' Lodovic told The
Associated Press.
   Lodovic, 26, of Benin, in West Africa, said police applied
electric prods to his face and body and beat him when they took him
and two other Africans into custody Dec. 31. He said he did not try
to resist the police.
   One of the other students, Alpha Robinson of Gambia, also has
been ordered to leave China after serving two weeks of
``disciplinary detention.''
   A third African, Alex Dzabaku Dosoo of Ghana, was taken from jail
to a state-run guesthouse, where he remains under house arrest. He
faces criminal charges in connection with the Dec. 24 brawl that set
off five days of anti-African demonstrations in the eastern China
city.
   Three Chinese also have been given 15-day sentences in connection
with the brawl.
   At the time Lodovic was taken into custody, he was among nearly
140 other African students being held by Chinese officials at a
hostel in suburban Nanking. Other students present said they saw
police using electric prods, but Lodovic is the first to say he was
a victim of attacks.
   Chinese authorities have denied any students were beaten or
shocked.
   The other African students in Nanking since have returned to
their schools from the hostel, where authorities had held them to
keep them from fleeing the city. They were trying to escape mobs of
Chinese youths who were demanding punishment for Africans involved
in the Christmas Eve fight in which 11 Chinese were injured.
   The brawl began after African men brought Chinese women to a
dance. It was followed by incidents in three other Chinese cities
involving African students. About 500 African students at the
Beijing Languages Institute on Sunday were in the 11th day of a
class boycott to protest charges by Chinese students that an African
had assaulted a Chinese student.
   Lodovoc arrived by train from Nanking with three other Africans,
two from Ghana and one other from Benin. They said they hoped to
leave China as soon as possible.
   All four attended Hehai University, the scene of the Dec. 24
fight.
   Lodovoc denied Chinese charges he and other Africans started the
fight, saying he was attacked from behind by Chinese when arguing
with those guarding the gate at the dance.
   The 1,500 African students on scholarships in China have long
complained of racial discrimination, and there have been sporadic
clashes in the past.
   Kwadwo Kwakye, acting head of the Ghana Embassy, said Sunday his
government's decision on whether to remove its 26 students from
China depends on how the Chinese handle the case of Alex Dosoo, the
Ghana student who remains in detention in Nanking.
   Kwakye said Dosoo has yet to be formally charged 15 days after
his arrest, and if he is not released ``we will have problems.''
</TEXT>
