<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Rushdie     01-15 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Rushdie,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bookseller To Remove Rushdie Book Following Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Spelling of W H Smith in 2nd graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bookseller will remove the controversial book
``Satanic Verses'' from its 430 stores in Britain, company officials
were quoted as saying Sunday after a rally against the novel.
   The Sunday Times and The Mail on Sunday reported that officials
of W H Smith and Sons Ltd. said their decision was made because the
book was not selling well but that opposition to the novel spurred
them to pull the book from stores earlier than planned.
   Police said 1,500 people rallied Saturday in the industrial city
of Bradford against the book, by Indian-born author Salman Rushdie.
   The rally was organized by the city's council of mosques, and a
copy of the book was burned, said a police spokesman who refused to
be identified.
   The book, which is condemned by Moslems as blasphemous and has
been banned in Saudi Arabia and India, highlights an Indian actor's
internal struggle against the forces of evil.
   ``It is a commercial consideration. We are not bowing to
pressure,'' The Times quoted Smith managing director Malcolm Field
as saying.
   ``But we have to bear in mind that a whole shop could be
threatened by this sort of thing,'' he said.
   The bookseller's retail marketing director, Terence Ludbird, said
if the book had been selling well it would have been kept on the
shelves, The Mail reported. It said Ludbird told the newspaper the
decision to pull it from stores had already been made when the
Bradford rally occurred.
   After the rally, ``police advised us to stop selling it ... so we
removed it from the shelves ahead of schedule,'' Ludbird was quoted
as saying.
   Police said they could not comment on Ludbird's comments.
   Rushdie, who lives in London, was quoted as telling The Sunday
Times, ``This is a very sad day, not only for me, but for English
literature.''
   The newspaper also reported that the ambassadors of Pakistan,
Qatar and Somalia have met with Home Office Minister John Patten to
protest the book. The report did not say when their visits took
place.
</TEXT>
