<FIRST>r a AM-DrugTest     01-15 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Test,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Kit Helps Parents Check Children for Drug Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new kit teaches parents to test children as
young as 7 for drug use by examining their eyes daily with a
flashlight, but some drug abuse experts say it will just erode trust
between parent and child.
   ``Seven years of age? That's like a Nazi kind of thing!,'' said
Linda Paire, Santa Ana clinic director of the Orange County Drug
Abuse Program.
   But Dave Hannah, president of Athletes for a Strong America, who
says he uses the eye test on his two sons daily, said last week that
parents need to work together with their children to stop the
growing drug problem in America.
   And the steps should begin around age 7, when some surveys find
children are first being exposed to drugs, he said.
   ``We live in a world today where drugs are rampant. If parents
start with their kids when they are young and team up (and use the
kit), it will be like brushing your teeth,'' he said.
   Athletes for a Strong America, a non-profit group based in
Irvine, markets the $49.95 kit, called ``The Winners Program.'' It
includes a videotape, audio tapes, written material and a medical
flashlight.
   It teaches parents to make the sort of checks common in roadside
sobriety tests, looking for redness in the white of the eye, a
too-large or too-small pupil, the pupil's ability to constrict when
exposed to light, the eye's ability to track a moving object from
side to side without jumping, and the eyes' ability to converge on
an object that is brought close to the face.
   But Paire questioned the effectiveness of such tests.
   ``There's a lot better ways to prevent drug abuse in your kids,''
she said. `Even the best urine tests we have today are not
foolproof. ... There are so many other things that could cause so
many similar reactions that I would hate a parent or teacher to pin
it on drugs.''
   Rene Topalian, assistant director of drug abuse services for the
Los Angeles County Health Department, said that two years ago, ``a
group marketed a kit for parents to test urine and it didn't get
anywhere.''
   ``Everything we try to project in prevention is to not take
intrusive measures as home, Topalian said, calling for parents to be
conscientious and work to develop the child's self-esteem.
   Hannah said the videotaped test instructions show parents how to
use the test without alienating their children.
   ``I have two sons (ages 18 and 21) and I test their eyes every
day,'' said Hannah, a former college football player.
   ``It's not that I don't trust them; they have never done
anything. But taking crack just one time can ruin a child's life.''
   About 3,500 kits have been sold in the past six months, Hannah
said. It has been marketed only at conferences and not yet widely
distributed. The organization makes $5 which is reinvested in the
program, and the salesperson makes $25, he said.
   ``There are probably high-risk situations where a parent is
desperate, but I wouldn't advocate it as primary prevention,'' said
Andy Johnson, a social psychologist with the University of Southern
California's School of Medicine who deals with drug-abuse. ``What
does it do in terms of trust between parent and child?
   ``But if the child is already using or is trying to hide it, it's
not a bad idea,'' he said.
   The test was developed with the help of Dr. Forest Tennant, a
drug adviser to the National Football League, the Los Angeles
Dodgers and the California Highway Patrol. Tennant advocates that
parents, schoolteachers and coaches learn the basics of the test so
they can understand the effects of drugs on the body.
</TEXT>
