<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-RadioPanic     01-15 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Radio Panic,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Panics Listeners with Fictional Death Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's state-run radio received dozens of
phone calls from alarmed listeners after it broadcast a review of a
new play in which a fictional Israeli prime minister shoots himself,
officials said Sunday.
   The report included parts of the play, including one sequence in
which a sports broadcaster covering a basketball game is suddenly
interrupted with a news flash.
   ``We have to stop the broadcast of the basketball game. A report
received just now says that the prime minister was found tonight
dead in his study. His personal handgun was on the floor nearby. A
police spokesman said there was no doubt that the prime minister
committed suicide,'' the broadcaster says in the play.
   The portion played on the radio also had the broadcaster saying
the prime minister had left a note saying he learned a newspaper was
to publish a report alleging he embezzled $1 million dollars from
government funds.
   ``We received dozens of phone calls from alarmed listeners, in
spite of the fact that at the start of the review, we warned that
the report was only fictional,'' said Ziva Levin, a spokeswoman for
the Israel Broadcast Authority.
   The review was broadcast on both morning and evening newscasts
Saturday, which are popular with the Israelis, most of whom stay at
home because of the Jewish Sabbath.
   The dramatic portion of the review was similar in technique to
the famous 1938 Orson Welles' radio adaptation of H.G. Wells' novel
``War of the Worlds,'' which shocked radio audiences in the United
States.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's spokesman, Avi Pazner, said
Shamir did not hear the broadcast.
   The play, titled ``The Leak,'' was written by journalist Matti
Golan and is to open soon in Tel Aviv. It focuses on a newspaper
reporter who is fed leaks by a power-hungry defense minister seeking
to overthrow the country's premier.
</TEXT>
