<SECOND>AM-Bomb Threat,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Threat Forces Plane to Land in Cyprus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Search of plane to begin 5 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb threat by someone claiming to
represent an anti-U.S. underground group forced an Olympic Airways
jet to abort its flight Sunday from Greece to Thailand and land in
Cyprus, airport sources said.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Flight 437
carried 421 passengers and crew.
   About an hour after the morning flight left Athens for Bangkok, a
message was phoned to Olympic Airways in Athens saying the flight
carried a bomb planted by the Nov. 17 Movement, the sources said.
   The organization is an anti-U.S. underground group that claimed
responsibility for assassinating CIA station chief Richard Welch in
1975 and killing 11 other U.S. personnel in Greece as well as people
the group accused of collaborating with the 1967-74 military
dictatorship.
   The group's name refers to the date of a 1973 attack on
university students by troops during the military regime.
   After the threat, the airline ordered its pilot to land in
Cyprus, and passengers and crew left the Boeing 747 immediately. The
airport sources said the plane would remain isolated at Larnaca
Airport for several hours until the baggage was removed and searched.
   Police first said they would begin searching the luggage after
the scheduled arrival time in Thailand, but airport workers worried
about their security said they refused to take part until later.
