<FIRST>r a AM-Bush-Everglades     01-15 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Everglades,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Environmentalists Hoping For Help From Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-100 Days, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARCO ISLAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While President-elect George Bush plied
waters off the Florida Keys for bonefish, environmentalists and
politicians gathered near here hoped Bush's interest in the state's
natural resources will be reflected in his presidency.
   ``After eight lost years in the Reagan administration, I think
the entire conservationist community is very excited, a little ill
at ease, anxious to see what happens,'' said Nathaniel Reed, a
former undersecretary of the Interior and a leading Florida
environmentalist who advised Bush during his presidential campaign.
   Reed was among more than 200 environmentalists, politicians and
government officials attending the fourth annual Everglades
Coalition meeting over the weekend, as Bush was fishing to the
southeast, on the other side of the Everglades National Park and
Florida Bay.
   Florida officials, realizing the state's runaway growth is
threatening its water supply and killing off species of plants and
animals, in the past decade have started ambitious land-buying and
restoration projects. But their efforts have gone against the tide
of Reagan administration policy that made economic benefits a
priority in federal lands.
   ``I find it of particular interest that he comes to the Florida
Keys,'' said Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla. ``He may have a special
interest in Florida's environment and take more than a bureaucratic
look at it.''
   Since his election, Bush has twice vacationed in South Florida,
and environmentalists consider his love for fishing significant.
   ``He actively participates in the environment, and one of the
first things to go when you have damage is the fishing,'' said
Charles Lee, vice president of the Florida Audubon Society.
   Environmentalists saw further signs of Bush's interest when the
president-elect met with Everglades National Park Superintendent
Mike Finley.
   In the hastily arranged meeting Saturday at Islamorada, Finley
said he found Bush interested in the many problems facing the
Everglades.
   Reed called it significant that Bush described himself during the
campaign as an environmentalist, using a term conservatives tend to
link to liberal Democrats, Reed said.
   The Reagan administration, Reed said, caused a ``brain drain'' of
bright youths from the federal environmental agencies because they
were frustrated, and also lost valuable time for conservation
efforts.
   He said Bush needs to make sure his environmental agencies and
Interior Department start out with enthusiasm and ``a can-do
attitude'' that will rally conservationists.
   A priority for Florida environmentalists is adding at least
105,000 acres to the Everglades National Park, but officials said
obtaining the land and federal funding will be difficult.
   Florida Gov. Bob Martinez, who was a national co-chairman for the
Bush campaign, will meet this week in Washington with incoming
Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan and William Reilly, whom Bush named
as director of the Environmental Protection Agency.
   ``I kind of think the president's going to enjoy fishing out that
way, and anything we can tie ourselves to to show what needs to be
done, we certainly need to do that,'' Martinez said.
</TEXT>
