<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     01-15 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Militias Clash; Syrian Troops Move Near Security Zone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias clashed twice
in Beirut's southern slums Sunday, and the Red Cross removed 20
decomposed corpses from a south Lebanon battlefront after arranging
a ``mercy cease-fire.''
   The Syrian army sent 50 troops close to Israel's self-proclaimed
security zone in south Lebanon to prevent the inter-Shiite fighting
from spreading to east Lebanon's Bekaa valley, police said.
   They said the first clash broke out at dawn between fighters of
the mainstream Amal militia and the fundamentalist Hezbollah, or
Party of God, in south Beirut's Hajjaj district. It lasted one hour.
   The second clash flared also for an hour after nightfall in south
Beirut's sprawling Bourj el-Barajneh district, according to police.
No casualties were reported.
   Hezbollah's chief spokesman proposed a six-point peace plan,
including an immediate cease-fire. There was no response from Amal,
which is fighting the pro-Iranian Hezbollah for control of Lebanon's
1 million Shiites.
   As the sound of grenade blasts and gunfire echoed across the
capital, two bombs went off within one minute in garbage dumps at
west Beirut's commercial district of Hamra.
   Police said there were no casualties or serious damage and that
no group claimed responsibility.
   The Syrians dismantled street barricades and sandbag positions
set up by Amal and Hezbollah in the southwestern Bekaa village of
Sohmor, police reported.
   It was the first time Syrian troops had entered Sohmor since
Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon, said a police spokesman who
cannot be identified under standing regulations.
   Sohmor is five miles north of the Israeli ``security zone,'' a
six- to 10-mile wide strip of land policed by Israeli troops and the
South Lebanon Army, a predominantly Christian militia allied with
Israel.
   The Lebanese Red Cross said its workers entered the embattled
village of Jbaa in south Lebanon's Apple Province and evacuated 20
corpses in six ambulances Sunday afternoon.
   A Red Cross spokesman said the bodies were of 11 Amal fighters
and nine Hezbollah fighters killed in Jbaa over the last five days.
   He said three other Amal victims were buried in Jbaa before the
convoy rolled out with the 20 corpses for burial at their native
villages.
   Jbaa is the key to a 9-square-mile enclave controlled by about
500 Hezbollah fighters. An estimated 1,000 Amal militiamen are
besieging the enclave, vowing to move in on their foes when their
supplies run out.
   ``We shall remain there. Even if we run out of ammunition, we
shall fight with stones. There are plenty of stones there,'' said
Hezbollah's chief spokesman Sheik Ibrahim Amin at a news conference
in south Beirut.
   Amin decribed Amal leader Nabih Berri as ``a bloodthirsty
pharoah'' and called for a six-point peace process including an
immediate cease-fire in south Beirut and south Lebanon; lifting of
Amal's food blockade on Hezbollah's enclave around Jbaa;
renunciation by Amal of its avowed policy of uprooting Hezbollah
from Lebanon; and dialogue between Amal and Hezbollah to lay down a
political and security formula for peaceful coexistence.
   There was no immediate response from Amal, whose spokesmen have
previously ruled out any truce.
   Hezbollah advocates establishment of an Iranian-patterned Islamic
republic in Lebanon.
   Syria backs the more secular Amal, which resents Iran's influence
and has been fighting since April to evict Hezbollah from Beirut's
Shiite-populated southern slums and predominantly Shiite south
Lebanon.
   Asked about Amal's accusations that Hezbollah, by kidnapping
foreigners, was tainting the reputation of Shiites, Amin said,
``Berri is speaking for America and Israel. We, irrespective of our
view on kidnapping foreigners, form the cornerstone for fighting
foreigners. Yes, this is an honor for us.''
   Asked whether the abduction of foreigners was legitimate, Amin
said, ``What I'm interested in is the continuation of the battles
against the enemies.''
   Hezbollah is believed to be the umbrella of extremist factions
holding most of the 15 foreign hostages in Lebanon. They include
nine Americans.
</TEXT>
