<DOCNO> AP890115-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-15-89 1633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Arafat     01-15 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arafat,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Ready For Peace Talks, Looks To Finland For Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat said Sunday he
is ready to begin international talks on Middle East peace, and he
sought the help of this neutral nation to get peace moves started.
   In a television interview on the eve of his arrival for an
official visit, Arafat urged Israel to respond to what he called the
PLO peace initiative, but he charged that Israel lacked strong
leadership.
   Asked about Israel's readiness for direct peace talks under U.N.
supervision, Arafat said: ``If they really mean that, then I have
said if there is an agreement on it, let's start right away with
international negotiations.''
   The chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization was
interviewed by Finnish state television at his Tunisian headquarters
before leaving for a two-day visit starting Monday.
   Extra police patrols were in downtown Helsinki and airport
security procedures were tightened several days ago in preparation
for Arafat's arrival.
   PLO officials here said Arafat would seek to persuade Finland to
lead the European neutral countries in recognizing the state of
Palestine declared Nov. 15 by the PLO's parliament-in-exile.
   ``Finland could have an important part in the peace negotiations,
because Finland is known for its neutrality and its desire to work
for peace everywhere,'' Arafat said.
   Zuheir Al Wazir, director of the PLO's Helsinki information
office, said the question of recognizing Palestine ``will certainly
be on the agenda'' of Arafat's talks.
   ``Finland and the other European neutral countries could take the
initiative and follow the other countries which have already
recognized the independent state of Palestine,'' he told the
Associated Press.
   The European neutrals are Finland, Sweden, Switzerland, and
Austria.
   A Finnish Foreign Ministry official, briefing reporters at the
outset of Arafat's two-day visit, said Finland cannot recognize
states that have no internationally accepted borders, even though
Helsinki welcomed the declaration of independence.
   Finland renewed a standing invitation to Israel's foreign
minister last week, after learning that Arafat had agreed to visit
Helsinki.
   The invitation to Arafat, issued last month, reflected an
apparent change in policy toward the PLO leader, who last month
recognized Israel's right to exist and renounced terrorism.
   ``PLO policy has publicly changed in a reassuring way and many
countries have noticed this. So have we,'' said the Foreign Ministry
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Arafat's Dec. 15 declaration led to the lifting of a 13-year ban
by the United States on contacts with the PLO. Las week, Britain
sent its top Foreign Office expert on Mideast affairs to Tunis to
meet Arafat.
   A senior PLO official said the organization's dialogue with the
United States will continue at its present level after
President-elect George Bush takes office, the Kuwait News Agency
reported Sunday.
   ``The aim of this dialogue is to explore and understand the real
U.S. ideas, opinions and trends,'' the agency quoted Khaled
Al-Hassan as saying in an interview with the Kuwait daily Al-Rai
Al-Aam. He is a member of the PLO's central committee.
   Finland had considered inviting Arafat in 1982 but rejected the
idea, arguing that Finland recognized only states, not organizations.
   The Foreign Ministry official admitted that seven years ago, it
was not seen as politically justifiable or prudent to invite the PLO
chief.
   The Finns have a tradition of good connections with Israel, which
kept an interest section in Finland's embassy in Moscow after the
Soviets severed diplomatic ties in 1967.
   Two year ago, the Finns held the first official meeting between
Israeli and Soviet delegations, a step toward reestablishing formal
contacts.
   Officials said Arafat would have formal talks with Foreign
Minister Kalevi Sorsa. He also was scheduled to meet Prime Minister
Harri Holkeri and President Mauno Koivisto.
</TEXT>
