<DOCNO> AP890115-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-15-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NorthKorea-Japan     01-15 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Korea-Japan,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Blasts Takeshita's Remarks On Hirohito</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea on Sunday sharply criticized Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita of Japan for eulogizing Emperor Hirohito,
describing the late monarch as a war criminal and ``a sworn enemy of
the Korean people.''
   The North's official Korean Central News Agency called
Takeshita's comments ``an intolerable challenge and insult'' to
Koreans and other Asians who were victims of Japanese militarism
before and during World War II.
   Hirohito, 87, died Jan. 7 after a 62-year reign that included
Japan's colonial rule over Korea and military incursions into much
of Asia before its defeat in 1945.
   In remarks after Hirohito's death, Takeshita said the emperor had
``resolutely brought to an end the war that had broken out in spite
of his wishes.''
   Historians are divided on Hirohito's war role, and on whether he
could have prevented the war.
   ``As the world knows, Hirohito is the chief war criminal who
unleashed the Pacific war as the supreme ruler of Japan,'' the North
Korean news agency said in the English-language report, monitored in
Tokyo.
   ``In particular, he is a sworn enemy of the Korean people, for he
was the chief criminal in enforcing the prolonged colonial rule of
Japanese imperialism over Korea,'' it said.
   The news agency charged that Takeshita was attempting to portray
the emperor as ``an apostle of peace'' in order to justify
continuing Japanese militarism.
   It also criticized Japanese government control over school
history textbooks and their portrayal of the country's war role, and
visits by Japanese officials to Yasukuni Shrine, a Shinto shrine
honoring Japan's war dead.
   Newspapers in South Korea this past week also criticized
Takeshita's remarks. On Thursday, dozens of South Korean students
demonstrated in front of the Japanese Embassy in Seoul demanding
that Takeshita apologize, and some students attacked the nearby
Japanese cultural center with firebombs.
</TEXT>
