<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0680 01-15 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Pledge to Keep Supplying Arms to Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-12 `In his...in April.' to UPDATE with Pakistani
reax and calls for new talks between guerrillas and Moscow; guerrilla leader
comments. no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union vowed Sunday to
continue supplying arms to the Afghan government after Soviet troops
withdraw and expressed confidence Kabul can successfully battle
rebels, an official report said.
   The report seemed to signal a Soviet intention to meet a Feb. 15
U.N. deadline for pulling out all its troops from Afghanistan, and
it dampened speculation the Soviets might drop support of Kabul's
Marxist government.
   ``If war is imposed on the Afghan government ... it will be
forced to counter this with force of arms, and it has this force,''
the official Afghan news agency quoted Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze as saying.
   ``The present regime has every opportunity to endure, and in case
the war goes on, the Soviet arms supplies will also be continued,''
he was quoted as saying.
   Shevardnadze gave the interview, which was also carried by the
Soviet news agency Tass, at the close of three days of intensive
talks with Afghan President Najib and other government leaders. The
minister then left for Moscow.
   A Pakistani Foreign Ministry spokesman, asked to comment on
Shevardnadze's statement, called it ``public posturing.''
   ``Shevardnadze cannot come to Kabul and say `Gentlemen, we are
going to ditch you, so you make your own arrangements for survival,'
'' the spokesman said at a news briefing.
   Pakistan and the United States support the guerrillas in their
bid to topple the Marxist government.
   The Pakistani spokesman, speaking anonymously in line with
goverment rules, said his government is encouraging Moscow and the
Afghan resistance based in Pakistan and Iran to negotiate again
toward forming a broad-based government.
   A meeting this month between the Pakistan-based guerrillas and
Yuli Vorontsov, the Soviet first deputy foreign minister and
ambassador to Afghanistan, ended in stalemate when the resistance
refused to allow Najib's Peoples Democratic Party of Afghanistan in
a future government.
   The idea behind the current diplomatic flurry is to put a
government in place in Kabul that can prevent a bloodbath after a
Soviet pullout under terms of U.N.-mediated Geneva accords signed in
April.
   Resistance leader Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, in Iran Sunday,
stressed the need for a united rebel alliance to avoid that
situation.
   ``Before the Russians leave, our organization should form a
government with a single leadership in order to avoid bloodshed
later,'' the Islamic Republic News Agency reported quoted him as
saying.
   Mojaddidi represents a seven-group Sunni Moslem alliance in
Pakistan. The guerrillas in Iran are Shiite Moslem.
   Mojaddidi said the fall of the Soviet-backed Kabul government
will automatically follow after the Soviets withdraw their troops,
but he warned that the guerrillas must be able to fill that vacuum
or face possible bloodshed, the official Iranian news agency said.
   In his statement, Shevardnadze referred to the pullout of Soviet
troops, saying, ``We were and are convinced of the fact that
Afghanistan has patriotic forces capable of protecting, on their
own, the gains of people and democratic institutions in the past few
years,'' the agency said.
   Western diplomats report that the final withdrawal of the
remaining 50,000 Soviet troops began in earnest in early January.
   Guerrillas backed by Pakistan and the United States control large
areas of the countryside and are attacking supply convoys within a
few miles of the capital.
   In its report, Tass said the rebels were trying to cut the supply
of necessities to the capital in an economic blockade.
   The Soviets moved in their forces nearly a decade ago after a
Soviet-backed Marxist coup. They eventually sent more than 100,000
troops, but about half of them left already under the Geneva accords.
</TEXT>
