<SECOND>AM-Bomb Suspects,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Suspects May Have Targeted Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONGMONT, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five people arrested with enough plastic
explosives to blow up three city blocks have been linked to white
supremacist groups and may have been targeting several police
stations, authorities said.
   One of the suspects told officials from the U.S. Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms that the group wanted to blow up some
police stations, said Sgt. George Dunphy, spokesman for the Boulder
County Sheriff's Department.
   Gary Wurm, resident agent in charge of the federal agency in
Denver, would not confirm that and Dunphy provided no other details
Sunday.
   Meanwhile, officials were investigating the five men's possible
ties to right-wing organizations.
   ``We suspect that they are'' members of white supremacist groups,
said Longmont Detective Jack Kimmett.
   The five suspects were arrested after a raid at a motel Friday
where agents posed as would-be buyers for the explosives, which
authorities suspect had been stolen from a mine in September.
   At the motel and in a raid on a Fort Collins home rented by one
of the suspects, Jeffery Rudolph of Akron, authorities found more
than 300 pounds of powerful plastic explosives, thousands of rounds
of ammunition, bullet-proof jackets, several weapons and right-wing
books and magazines about survival tactics and terrorism.
   Richard S. Baxter, 51, of Fort Collins; Andrew W. Ferguson, 29,
of Fort Collins; Jon A. Kobert, 29, of Fort Collins; and Rudolph,
29, were transferred Saturday from the Boulder County Jail to the
Denver City Jail. They were being held by the U.S. marshal's office
on federal charges of dealing in explosives without a license.
   Bond arrangements for the four were to be made before a U.S.
magistrate Thursday.
   Evelyn J. Moschetti, 18, of Laporte, remained in the Boulder jail
for investigation of county charges of possession of explosives and
conspiracy to possess. Her first court appearance was scheduled for
Tuesday.
   The arrests culminated a month-long investigation by federal
officials with assistance from the Longmont police and the sheriff's
department.
   Authorities said the investigation stemmed from the theft of
explosives from the John Jay mine near Jamestown in September.
