<FIRST>u i AM-Libya-Non-Aligned     01-15 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-Non-Aligned,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Asks Non-Aligned Nations For Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya said on Sunday that non-aligned
nations should support each other if attacked by a nation that is
not a member of their movement.
   The proposal was included in a paper submitted during a special
confrerence of the non-aligned movement. The 101-member organization
began meeting on Friday to find ways of modernizing the group and
increasing its effectiveness.
   The Libyan paper demanded ``the committment of member countries
to provide political and material support to any counrty among them
subjected to aggression from a state or states not belonging to the
movement.''
   The paper also said member states should refuse to allow foreign
forces to use their territory to attack another state.
   The Libyan demands appeared to be a direct appeal for support
from the non-aligned movement against threatened U.S. military
action to neutralize a Libyan factory allegedly built to manufacture
chemical weapons.
   Libya accused the United States of unprovoked aggression
following the Jan. 4 downing of two Libyan fighters over the
Mediterranean by American jets.
   The U.S. Defense Department said the shooting was not related to
the chemical factory and that the American jets attacked defensively
when the Libyan jets were about to attack.
   Libya has claimed the jets were unarmed and on a reconnaissance
mission over international waters. It claims the plant at Rabta
produces pharmaceuticals.
   The non-aligned movement, founded in 1961, initially was designed
to represent countries that did not want to choose sides in the
U.S.-Soviet superpower rivalry.
</TEXT>
