<FIRST>r a AM-Housewares-Future     01-15 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housewares-Future,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Dog Toilet, Anyone? Exhibitors Show New Products for Pets, People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vacuum cleaner that roasts mites and a
wall-mounted brush that attracts cats with the smell of catnip were
among more than 3 million products on exhibit Sunday at a show for
commercial buyers.
   But nothing was so offbeat at the International Housewares
Exposition as the Pet Flush, an outdoor toilet bowl for dog waste.
   ``This flushes doggie doo down the sewer,'' said Russ Xepoleas,
vice president for sales at Blue Magic Products Inc., of Stockton,
Calif. ``The hardest part is getting your dog to sit on it.'' The
football-sized bowl is designed to be attached to an outside drain
also hooked up to a water supply.
   The exhibit, which includes electronics, bakeware, cleaning
items, furniture and home office products, is held by the National
Housewares Manufacturers Association to help manufacturers sell
their products. It has been held 89 times since 1939.
   Thousands of wholesale and retail buyers are expected to attend
the show, which began Sunday and runs through Wednesday. Buyers
represent every area of distribution including hardware and
drugstore chains, department and discount stores, catalog showrooms
and gift and specialty shops.
   New specialty pet items included a cardboard cat playhouse. Cats
can sit in it, said designer Linda Coffey of Minneapolis.
   ``Our customer is the Bloomingdale's and Neiman Marcus
customer,'' said Ms. Coffey. She said the cat house is painted with
``a combination of classical columns and modern cat imagery.''
   There was a vanilla-flavored edible flying disk for dogs; the
Cat-A-Comb brush that attracts cats with its catnip scent and
removes hair as the cat brushes against it; and the vacuum cleaner
with a heat chamber inside that kills bugs after it sucks them out
of carpets and furniture.
   For humans, there were items promoting convenience such as a
battery-operated vacuum cleaner and a butane-fueled hair dryer that
does away with tangled electrical cords.
   New home safety products included an air filter system that
claims to remove radon gas from buildings, a smoke alarm that plays
recorded messages when set off and plastic bags that people can wear
on their heads to escape from house fires without suffering smoke
inhalation.
</TEXT>
