<FIRST>r i AM-LibyanPlant     01-15 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libyan Plant,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: No Hard U.S. Evidence Libya Plant Produces Poison Gas, Bonn
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German experts who examined U.S.
evidence said they found no hard proof that a Libyan plant was built
to produce chemical weapons, a newspaper reported Sunday.
   The conservative Bonn newspaper Die Welt said Sunday documents
shown by U.S. officials to the team of West Germans last week failed
to show the plant in Rabta, 60 miles southwest of the capital
Tripoli, was definitely intended to manufacture poison gas.
   However, Die Welt said Bonn officials ``were not denying'' news
reports last week that U.S. intelligence agencies intercepted
telephone conversations of Libyan officials in August asking West
German chemical companies for help in cleaning up a chemical spill
in Rabta.
   The newspaper telexed its report to news agencies in advance of
its publication Monday.
   Chief government spokesman Friedhelm Ost said Saturday the U.S.
information ``indicates a number of German firms as well as
companies from several nations made deliveries for the Libyan
chemical plant,'' but that officials had not found evidence to
warrant prosecution.
   ``A preliminary evaluation of the documents provided by the
Americans shows that the material is nothing beyond what we already
know about so far and would not stand up in court,'' Ost said in a
statement.
   The two West German companies under investigation are
Imhausen-Chemie of Lahr and the now-defunct I.B.I. Engineering of
Frankfurt.
   In newspaper interviews published Sunday in Britain and West
Germany, I.B.I. owner Ihsan Barbouti was quoted as saying he doubted
the Libyans were producing chemical weapons in Rabta.
   They were the first published interviews of Barbouti since he was
publicly linked to the plant.
   ``I was there five years and nobody had ever mentioned that it
was a poison gas factory,'' the West Berlin newspaper Morgenpost
quoted Barbouti as saying. ``All the blueprints for the
pharmaceutical factory were all over the office, everyone could see
them.''
   Barbouti, a 61-year-old Iraqi architect who lives in London, was
quoted as saying he received a contract from the Libyans to build a
large manufacturing complex but that the plant in question was built
separately by the Libyans.
   ``I believe firmly that they (the Libyans), as far as I know, did
not produce poison gas while I was there and are not producing it
now,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Barbouti was also quoted as saying that companies from West
Germany, Japan, Denmark, Yugoslavia, Belgium, Italy and France
delivered equipment for the Rabta complex.
   In his interview with the Observer newspaper of London, Barbouti
was quoted as saying the complex was to include a foundry, a plastic
molding workshop, maintenance and engineering workshops and storage
hangars for Libya's vast imports.
   Barbouti was quoted as saying the Libyans decided in 1985 to add
a pharmaceutical factory to the site ``so that they could make their
own drugs under license.''
   ``I saw a plan to produce around 50 different drugs,'' he was
quoted as saying.
   When asked who built the pharmaceutical plant, he was quoted as
saying ``The Libyans themselves.''
</TEXT>
