<FILEID>AP-NR-01-15-89 1915EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DesignerDrugs     01-15 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Designer Drugs,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Street Drug PCP Found To Protect Against Some Brain Injury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The street drug known as PCP or ``angel
dust'' can protect against damage to the brain following a heart
attack or stroke, researchers said Sunday.
   Specially designed drugs that can impart this beneficial
protection without causing the mental disruption that PCP produces
could be in use within five to 10 years, the researchers said at the
annual meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of
Science.
   Such drug relatives are often referred to as ``designer drugs,''
because they are carefully designed by pharmacologists to mimic some
but not all of the properties of a known drug.
   Angel dust, known technically as PCP or phencyclidine, is both a
stimulant and a depressant, and it induces a psychiatric state
similar to schizophrenia.
   Dr. Edward F. Domino of the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor,
who has studied PCP extensively, said that at least seven classes of
``designer drugs'' produce effects similar to PCP.
   One is an anesthetic called ketamine that is rarely used in the
United States but used frequently in the Third World because it is
easier to administer.
   It produces some of the same disorienting symptoms as does PCP,
but the symptoms don't last as long, Domino said, and they can be
controlled with tranquilizers.
   Ketamine shares the ability of PCP to protect the brain when it
has been deprived of oxygen, as can happen during a heart attack or
stroke.
   A drug related to ketamine could be given to heart attack or
stroke patients or to people about to undergo surgery to prevent
serious brain damage, Domino said.
   The National Institute on Drug Abuse is encouraging research in
the development of safer versions of ketamine and PCP, Domino said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890115-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-15-89 1918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Scotland-Storm     01-15 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotland-Storm,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gales Cause Flooding in Scotland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High winds and torrential rain swept
across Scotland on Sunday, flooding roads and knocking out electric
power in several areas, police and meteorologists said.
   The West Highland railway line north of Crianlarich, 40 miles
north of Glasgow, was closed by floodwaters in three places Sunday
night and power was cut in the remote Shetland Islands, 120 miles
off the northern tip of Scotland.
   No injuries were reported.
   The London Weather Center said winds gusted to 80 mph over the
Forth Road bridge at Edinburgh, to 114 mph on Collafirth Hill in the
Shetlands and to 130 mph at the summit of the 4,084-foot Cairn Gorm
mountain in central Scotland.
   The Automobile Association reported several main roads and some
minor ones closed by flooding, as the gales brought up to 3 inches
of rain in 48 hours, undermining road shoulders and bursting river
banks.
   In the north, police issued flood warnings and urged farmers to
take their animals in from low-lying ground.
   In the south, power was disrupted to 2,000 homes, mainly in
scattered areas of Fife, East Lothian, and the southwest when trees
fell on power lines or lines were damaged by the wind.
   The coast guard reported few serious problems but said bad
weather delayed some ships, including a freight ferry from Northern
Ireland to Ardrossan, 25 miles southwest of Glasgow.
   The London Weather Center said Scotland lay in the path of a mild
and moist southwesterly airstream of tropical origin.
</TEXT>
