<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Gorbachev     01-15 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Gorbachev,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Wants to Visit Britain Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev told Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher he would like to reschedule the official
visit to Britain that was scrapped because of the Armenian
earthquake, her office said Sunday.
   Soviet Ambassador Leonid Zamyatin visited Mrs. Thatcher for 45
minutes at her 10 Downing St. office Sunday night on his return from
Moscow and conveyed a message from Gorbachev on a number of
international issues, a spokeswoman at Downing Street said.
   In the message, Gorbachev confirmed his desire to pay an official
visit as soon as new dates could be set, she said on condition of
anonymity in keeping with British practice.
   Mrs. Thatcher replied that the Soviet leader would be welcome
whenever he chose to visit, the spokeswoman said.
   Gorbachev had been scheduled to visit Britain on his way back to
Moscow from the United States in early December, but the earthquake
that devastated Soviet Armenia struck Dec. 7 and he left the United
States immediately, returning directly home.
   Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, last were in Britain in December
1987 when they paid a fleeting visit to Brize Norton Royal Air Force
station in Oxfordshire, west of London.
   Mrs. Thatcher visited the Soviet Union in April 1987.
</TEXT>
