<FIRST>r a AM-ACEAwards     01-15 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ACE Awards,0862</SECOND>
<HEAD>Real-Life Dramas Win in Cable Industry's 10th Annual ACE Awards</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Embargoed for 9 p.m. EST. Time set by source.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three dramas dealing with contemporary issues,
``Mandela,'' ``Vietnam War Story'' and ``Tidy Endings,'' led Home
Box Office to a smashing victory Sunday in the cable industry's 10th
Annual ACE Awards.
   The trio of dramas won 13 awards as HBO captured a total of 35
Awards for Cable Excellence, four times more than the nearest
competitor, Arts &amp; Entertainment Network with eight. In all, HBO had
received 114 nominations in the 76 categories for which prizes were
given.
   Danny Glover, Alfre Woodard, Stockard Channing, Rip Torn, Robin
Williams, Billy Crystal, Jackie Mason and Billy Joel were among the
performers cited by the National Academy of Cable Programming. Lucy
Webb won her fourth consecutive ACE as best actress in a comedy
series for HBO's ``Not Necessarily the News.''
   ``Vietnam War Story,'' a 30-minute anthology series, won five
awards including best dramatic series. Wesley Snipes was named best
actor, and in the dramatic series category the show also won for
directing, writing and direction of photography. It had received 18
nominations, the most of any show.
   Pamela Reed was named best actress in a dramatic series for HBO's
``Tanner '88.''
   Glover and Ms. Woodard won as best actor and actress in a movie
or miniseries for ``Mandela,'' which got four ACEs in all. Glover
starred as Nelson Mandela, imprisoned South African founder of the
African National Congress, and Woodard was Winnie Mandela, his wife
and fellow activist. The drama also won for directing and film
editing.
   ``Tidy Endings,'' a playlet about settling the affairs of an AIDS
victim by his ex-wife and his homosexual lover, took four awards. It
was named best dramatic special and Ms. Channing won as best
actress. Her co-star, ``Torch Song Trilogy'' creator Harvey
Fierstein, won an ACE for writing, and another went to the director.
   ``The Race for the Double Helix'' was selected best movie or
miniseries. Juliet Stevenson also won as best supporting actress in
a movie or miniseries.
   ``Blackadder the Third'' on A&amp;E Network was picked as best comedy
series. HBO's ``On Location: Dennis Miller: Mr. Miller Goes to
Washington'' won as best comedy special.
   Crystal won as best actor in a comedy series for ``HBO Comedy
Hour Live: An All-Star Toast to the Improv.'' Williams was cited for
best performance in a comedy special for HBO's ``Comedy Relief
'87.'' Mason missed out for best performance but won as best writer
of a comedy special for HBO's ``On Location: Jackie Mason on
Broadway.''
   Billy Joel won as best performer in a music special for ``HBO
World Stage: Billy Joel Live from Leningrad.'' The show also won as
best music special.
   Daniel Massey was named best actor in a dramatic special for
``HBO Showcase: Intimate Contact.'' Rip Torn won as best supporting
actor in a movie or miniseries for HBO's ``Laguna Heat.''
   Peter Ustinov received an ACE as best informational or
documentary host for ``Peter Ustinov in China'' on the Discovery
Channel. Roy Firestone was named best sports host for ``Sports
Look'' on ESPN. Bernard Shaw of Cable News Network was named best
news anchor.
   Nearly 500 cable academy members and others in the production
community got to vote on the preliminary competition, which narrowed
the 1,214 entries to 324 finalists, and the final balloting. Votes
were tallied by an accounting firm. In addition to HBO's 35 awards
and A&amp;E's eight, here's how the other networks did: CNN five; Bravo
Cable Network, Discovery Channel, ESPN and Showtime four each;
Disney Channel three; Cinemax, Nickelodeon and USA Network two each;
and Lifetime, Prime Ticket and SuperStation TBS one each.
   HBO also received the ``Golden ACE,'' the cable industry's
highest honor, for its ``high impact'' programming. Its three
winning dramas were cited, as was ``Dear America: Letters Home from
Vietnam,'' which won an ACE as best dopcumentary special.
   Harry Anderson, star of NBC's ``Night Court'' and of cable comedy
specials, was host of the show at the Wiltern Theater. It was
produced by Moffitt-Lee Productions, whose ``Not Necessarily the
News'' on HBO has 13 ACEs over the years, the most for any show. The
awards presentation was carried live on 10 basic cable networks.
   Awards in the crafts and technical awards, and in some acting
categories, were made Saturday night at a dinner at the Beverly
Wilshire Hotel.
   The National Academy is a division of the National Cable
Television Association. It was created in 1985 to promote excellence
in cable programming. This past September, cable shows and
performers were included in the Emmy awards for the first time. The
cable industry said, however, that it would continue its own awards
program.
   The presentations were carried by Black Entertainment Television,
the CBN Family Channel, the Discovery Channel, Financial News
Network, Lifetime, Movietime, Nick at Nite, SuperStation TBS, Turner
Network Television, and USA Network.
   Nominations this year came from 24 cable programming networks, up
from 19 networks last year.
</TEXT>
