<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Party     01-15 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Party,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Presents Gorbachev and Other Candidates for Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party leadership's candidates for a
new national assembly include Mikhail S. Gorbachev and many
champions of his reforms, but not three members of the ruling
Politburo, news reports indicated Sunday.
   The party's policy-making Central Committee last week approved
the Politburo's candidates for the 100 seats allotted to the party
in the new Council of People's Deputies.
   The new council is to choose the membership of the Supreme Soviet
legislature and the nation's president, the post now held by
Gorbachev.
   One-third of the seats in the new 2,250-member assembly are
reserved for deputies directly elected by social organizations such
as the Communist Party and trade unions.
   The other two-thirds are to be filled by March 26 public
elections to choose deputies from the 15 Soviet republics and their
electoral districts.
   Many of those chosen in the territorial elections also are
expected to be members of the Communist Party, the only legal
political party in the Soviet Union.
   The elections, the first under political reforms championed by
Gorbachev, are to be open to an unlimited number of candidates.
Multiple candidates have already been nominated in some places, but
Western diplomats say the party's choice of 100 candidates for the
same number of seats will likely set a standard.
   The party's list of candidates for the seats it is allowed to
fill directly includes Gorbachev and Yegor K. Ligachev, who is
widely reported to be a conservative force on the Politburo. The
list was published by Pravda and other national newspapers on Sunday.
   Many intellectuals who support Gorbachev's drive for
``perestroika,'' or national restructuring, are among the party's
candidates, including economist Leonid Abalkin, scientist Yevgeny
Velikhov, writer Daniel Granin, economist Yevgeny Primakov and stage
actor Mikhail Ulyanov.
   Also chosen to represent the Communist Party is conservative
writer Vasily Belov, who has been linked to the leadership of the
right-wing Russian organization ``Memory'', which blames the
country's woes on a conspiracy that includes foreigners and Jews.
   All 12 members of the Politburo are included on the candidate
list, except Ukrainian party boss Vladimir V. Shcherbitsky, Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and Russian federation president
Vitaly I. Vorotnikov.
   Shcherbitsky and Vorotnikov could be chosen during local
elections in the republics where they have their power base.
Shevardnadze, a Georgian, may be elected to represent that southern
Soviet republic in the new council.
   Pravda said the party's election committee had found the Central
Committee's choices to be in conformity with the law. The 100
candidates are to be voted on by party leaders at a special March
15-16 meeting.
   The party's 20-million member rank and file will have a chance to
express opinions about the candidates, but will not get a chance to
vote, the Tass news agency has said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
