<FIRST>u i AM-Belgium-Kidnapping 1stLd-Writethru   01-15 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Kidnapping, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0701,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Former Prime Minister Believed Kidnapped</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with official saying ex-premier
believed kidnapped; picks up 4th graf `Vanden Boeynants...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Paul Vanden
Boeynants was reported missing and believed kidnapped, a prosecutor
said Sunday. An anonymous caller told a radio station the ex-leader
was abducted by a leftist group.
   The caller told the French-language RTBF network that 69-year-old
Vanden Boeynants, whose family reported him missing Saturday night,
was kidnapped by a group called the Revolutionary Socialist Brigade.
   Andre Vandoren, the deputy Brussels prosecutor, said officials
have never heard of the group. He quoted the caller as saying: ``We
have kidnapped Mr. Vanden Boeynants, the former prime minister. If
you do not believe us, contact his wife.''
   The caller led police to believe that kidnapping was the ``most
plausible'' explanation for Vanden Boeynants' disappearance,
Vandoren said.
   Officials said Vanden Boeynants arrived home by car at about 6
p.m. Saturday but never entered his residence. They said police
found a hearing aid, a pipe and a shoe belonging to him in his
garage.
   Vanden Boeynants, a Christian Democrat, has a long political
history marked by controversy.
   He entered Parliament in 1949 and served as prime minister
between 1966 and 1968, and again for several months in late 1978 and
early 1979. He also served several times as defense minister in the
1970s.
   In 1986, he received a three-year suspended sentence for tax
evasion, forgery and fraud as head of a Brussels meat-packing
company. At his sentencing, the judge said of Vanden Boeynants,
``tax evasion is your second nature.''
   In addition to his career in national politics, he served as
Brussels city councilor for more than 30 years.
   He was re-elected city councillor in elections on Oct. 9, 1987.
He tried to become mayor in negotiations for that job with other
parties but abandoned his bid at a tearful press conference on Oct.
12.
   In recent months, Vanden Boeynants has headed up a project to
develop the Atomium, the giant structure of an iron molecule that
towered over the 1958 world exposition here.
</TEXT>
