<FIRST>r a AM-KidnapRelease     01-15 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kidnap Release,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Allegedly Kidnapped By Florida Prison Escapees, Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old boy believed kidnapped by two
Florida prison escapees has turned up safe here 11 days later, and
the men are suspects in a string of armed robberies along the East
Coast, the FBI said Sunday.
   Ted Siegel on Sunday described his alleged captors _ Patrick
Hughes Paige and Anthony James Cokley _ as ``very hospitable,''
adding, ``They weren't brutal or anything.'' Smiling in an interview
with WBAL-TV, the honor student said his captivity was ``an
interesting experience.''
   Siegel told authorities he was released in Baltimore Saturday
night, along with the car he had been driving, but drove north on
Interstate 95 until he felt safe. Paige and Cokley drove off in
another car, he said. Siegel called his mother from a restaurant
about 30 miles north of Baltimore.
   Authorities were searching for Paige and Cokley, who escaped from
the Marion Correctional Institution in Lowell, Fla., on Jan. 3.
Siegel vanished shortly afterward while doing an errand for his
mother in her car.
   Siegel told authorities he was seized by Paige and Cokley from
the race area of Flamingo Farm in Lowell, where he lived with his
mother, a horse trainer, the FBI said.
   Siegel was to be escorted home by two sheriff's investigators. He
was expected home on Monday or Tuesday.
   The Marion County Sheriff's Office and the FBI said the escapees
are suspects in a string of armed robberies and burglaries.
   Cokley, 23, was serving a sentence for robbery. Paige, 21, was
incarcerated on grand theft and burglary convictions.
   Federal charges of kidnapping and interstate transportation of
stolen motor vehicles have been authorized by the U.S. Attorney's
office in Jacksonville, Fla., the FBI said.
</TEXT>
