<DOCNO> AP890115-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-15-89 2106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Flight103     01-15 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paper Says Israeli Spy Chief Claims Palestinian Group Planted Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Israeli intelligence official believes a
Palestinian group headed by reputed terror mastermind Abu Ibrahim
blew up Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland last month, a newspaper said
Sunday.
   The Sunday Post of Scotland quotes former Mossad officer Raphael
Eitan as saying he had ``no doubt'' the bombers were Ibrahim's
Iraqui-based May 15 Palestinian group, and that the bomb was made
there and probably carried on board the Boeing 747 by an unwitting
accomplice.
   The crash killed 270 people over Lockerbie, Scotland.
   The May 15 group has offices in Syria and Libya, as well as the
Iraqi capital, Eitan was quoted as saying.
   ``They are led by Abu Ibrahim, a qualified engineer,'' Eitan was
quoted as telling the newspaper. ``In the early days Ibrahim
received all his financial support from Iraqi intelligence, who
continue to provide him with cash and premises.
   ``May 15 has only 20 to 30 operatives who concentrate their
terrorist efforts on passenger airlines,'' Eitan was quoted as
saying.
   May 15 was the only Palestinian with the expertise to carry out
such attacks, Eitan was quoted as saying. ``Ibrahim spent five years
designing and perfecting the device which exploded over Lockerbie,''
he was quoted as saying.
   Eitan, who said he had been involved in investigating
booby-trapped suitcases since 1984, was quoted as saying:
   ``Ibrahim's detonator is so small it fits into the lock of the
suitcase. The explosive is made of plastic, not necessarily Semtex.
This plastic is extremely thin and looks like computer printout
paper so it is easily concealed.''
   ``In the past four years he has failed several times to carry out
a similar atrocity,'' Eitan was quoted as saying. ``In 1984, British
and West German intelligence intercepted five suitcases packed with
explosives which May 15 intended to plant on unsuspecting airline
passengers. Two were found in London, two were found in Frankfurt.''
   Asked to respond to the report, a spokeswoman at Scotland Yard
police headquarters said she could not comment on security matters.
Police in Lockerbie also had no comment.
   The newspaper also quotes Ian Geldard of The Institute for the
Study of Terrorism in London as saying May 15 ``certainly were the
principals in the earlier attempts to plant plastic explosives on
passenger jets.''
   Eitan headed the secret Israeli Defense Ministry unit that
supervised Jonathan Pollard, an American civilian employee of the
U.S. Navy who was sentenced to life in prison in March 1987 for
selling classified military documents to Israel.
   The episode was a blow to U.S.-Israel relations and Eitan left
his intelligence post after Pollard's 1985 arrest. He was given the
job of chairman of Israeli Chemicals Ltd., the largest state-owned
company.
   Investigators have determined that Flight 103 was bombed, and an
international police effort is under way to track down the
terrorists responsible.
   The London-based Sunday Express reported this week that
investigators were looking into the possibility that a U.S. soldier
unknowingly took the bomb aboard the jetliner.
   The newspaper said British and U.S. investigators were acting on
U.S. government reports that some U.S. soldiers had been approached
in West German nightclubs and offered thousands of dollars to carry
diamonds to New York. The paper said the soldiers instead may have
unwittingly carried the bomb.
   A U.S. Defense Department spokesman said in Washington late
Saturday night he had no information about the report.
   Another newspaper, The Sunday Telegraph, said the investigation
was being hampered by the recovery of baggage from the wreckage
which cannot be matched with anyone on board the plane.
   It said Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist squad also believed
luggage belonging to passengers who died was mistakenly placed on
other flights.
   The newspaper said police matching luggage to passengers is
essential to tracing the bombers.
   Scotland Yard had no comment on The Sunday Telegraph's report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
