<FIRST>r a AM-OutToPasture     01-15 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Out To Pasture,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Easy-going Police Horse To Retire, But Saved From Glue Factory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An easy-going horse with plenty of street smarts is
headed to pasture after a 20-year hitch with the Boston Police
Department, but the end of his road won't be a glue factory.
   A plot has been reserved for the 30-year-old Prescott at the
Angel View Pet Cemetery in Middleboro, said Patrolman Emilio ``Moe''
Ciriello, the city's top police horseman.
   Prescott, a stocky Morgan gelding who was 10 years old when he
joined the department, ``paid his dues over and over; he's done it
all,'' said Ciriello.
   ``Riots, strikes, parades, the marathon, busing, the Beatles,
Elvis Presley, Fenway Park. He's even made the Patriot's Day ride to
Lexington from the Old North Church with Paul Revere.
   ``But that's only half of it,'' Ciriello said. ``Prescott made a
horseman out of dozens of rookie riders. He's a clever, streetwise,
all-class horse. We want him as long as we can have him, but you
never know at his age.''
   Prescott was donated by former Mayor Kevin H. White to the
mounted unit, which has 23 horses and two ponies.
   ``It was probably the best gift the department ever got,'' said
groom Helen Henderson of Hyde Park, whose official title is
``hostler.''
   Prescott will spend his retirement at the stables with the other
horses, but he'll only be ridden on special occasions, hostler Joe
Catanese said Sunday.
</TEXT>
