<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Lekachman     01-15 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Lekachman,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economist Critical of Reagan Presidency Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Lekachman, an economist who taught at
several American universities and wrote two books critical of the
Reagan administration, has died. He was 68.
   Lekachman died at his home Saturday after a six-year battle with
cancer, said Ann Perryman, spokeswoman for Lehman College of the
City University of New York, where Lekachman was a professor.
   Two of his books on economics, ``The Age of Keynes,'' published
in 1966, and ``A History of Economic Ideas,'' published in 1959,
have been translated into several languages.
   He also wrote two books critical of the Reagan administration:
``Visions and Nightmares, America after Reagan,'' published in 1987,
and ``Greed is not enough, Reaganomics,'' published in 1982.
   Lekachman lectured frequently before business, labor, academic
and religious groups and participated in many radio and television
broadcasts.
   Lekachman taught at Barnard College from 1948 to 1965, then
joined the State University of New York at Stonybrook, where he
eventually became chairman of the Economics Department. He joined
the faculty at Lehman in 1973.
   He is survived by his wife, Eva.
</TEXT>
