<FILEID>AP-NR-01-15-89 2127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Boeing 1stLd-Writethru   01-15 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Boeing, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0686,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wiring Flaw Found in Boeing Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS five grafs with Boeing comment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British airline found crossed wires in a Boeing
757 during checks of the fire-warning systems for cargo holds after
similar problems turned up in two U.S. 757s, aviation officials said
Sunday.
   The cargo-compartment fault found in a Boeing 757 operated by Air
2000 was caused by switched plugs and immediately fixed, the British
Civil Aviation Authority said.
   The British airline flies from Gatwick airport south of London to
Orlando, Fla. and Mombasa, Kenya.
   No faults were reported in 39 other Boeing 757s operated by four
British airlines, the aviation authority said.
   Investigators are checking whether faulty wiring may have
contributed to the crash Jan. 7 of a British Midland Boeing 737 in
central England. Forty-four people were killed.
   Experts have speculated a flaw in wiring may have caused the
pilot of that plane to turn off the right engine after a fire
started in the left engine.
   The aviation authority ordered checks on the cargo-compartment
fire-warning systems of Boeing 757s on Friday after a U.S. alert the
same day.
   The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration gave U.S. airlines 72
hours to check whether cross-wiring in cargo holds might cause
sprinklers to go on in the wrong cargo hold in the event of a fire.
That order was issued after cross-wiring problems were found on two
Boeing 757s.
   Tom Cole, Boeing Commercial Airplane Co. spokesman in Seattle,
said the FAA directive was issued after problems with the two U.S.
757s were detected.
   On Sunday, Cole said Boeing was aware of the Air 2000 problem and
was having technical representatives in London look at it.
   He said problems with electrical hookups have been discovered in
several isolated incidents in recent years, including in a 747 and
in a 767. The 767 also involved wire confusion in the lower hold
fire suppression system.
   One of the two glitches found in U.S. 757s was discovered before
the plane was even delivered for use, he said.
   ``Whether this one (in England) is laid to the manufacturer, I
don't know,'' Cole said. ``But whosever fault it is, Boeing will
take steps that it doesn't happen again. Whether it's in the
assembling procedure or in the maintenance manuals, we'll take steps
to see that it doesn't reoccur.''

</TEXT>
