<HEAD>GM Executive Expected To Get No. 2 Pentagon Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Atwood Jr., vice chairman of General
Motors Corp., is expected to be named to the No. 2 position at the
Pentagon, according to a report published Sunday.
   Atwood, who has filled management positions at GM for 27 years,
is the top choice of John Tower, the defense secretary-designate, to
become deputy secretary, The New York Times reported.
   Quoting unidentified officials involved in the transition to a
new administration, the Times said the list of candidates, headed by
Atwood, also includes William Paul, senior vice president for
defense and space systems at United Technologies Corp., and Vincent
Cook, a vice president of International Business Machines Corp.
   Tower, a former chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee
and recently a consultant for several major military contractors,
was selected by President-elect Bush on Dec. 16.
   The deputy has responsibility for the Pentagon's daily operation,
and Bush and Tower want him to play a major role in cleaning up the
military procurement process in the wake of a fraud scandal last
year, the Times said.
   Atwood, 63, as vice chairman of GM, supervises divisions that
manufacture electronics and airplane systems for the Pentagon. An
engineer by profession, Atwood has a lot of experience in running
large industrial organizations, including GM's truck and bus group
and the Hughes Aircraft Co. after GM acquired it in 1985.
