<HEAD>Airliner Returns After Engine Catches Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINTHICUM, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines jet bound for Dallas
with 91 people aboard was forced to return to Baltimore-Washington
International Airport after an engine caught fire Sunday, an airline
spokesman said.
   Witnesses on the ground said they saw fire and smoke coming from
an engine of the plane, local television stations reported. The air
traffic control tower also reported sighting flames, said Susie
Robbins, American Airlines spokeswoman.
   Flight 201 took off at 7:53 a.m. and safely was on the ground
again shortly after 8 a.m., Ms. Robbins said. The 85 passengers were
put on other planes to reach their destinations, she said.
   A piece of the left engine apparently came loose and a compressor
stalled in the engine, prompting the pilot to shut down the engine,
Ms. Robbins said. She said the cause of the fire was not known. The
plane was a narrow-body MD80, manufactured by McDonnell-Douglas, she
said.
