<FIRST>r a AM-AilingSovietTeen     01-15 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ailing Soviet Teen,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Teen Headed for Arizona for Heart Exam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet teen-ager with a congenital heart defect
is due to arrive in the United States on Monday to undergo an
examination arranged by a great-aunt she has never met.
   Oksana Hlebkyna's congenital heart defect apparently could not be
treated in her hometown of Kiev, the capital of the Ukranian
republic of the Soviet Union. The 17-year-old's condition was
diagnosed seven years ago.
   Since then, her great-aunt, Kateryna Rosola, of Phoenix, has been
trying to bring her grandniece to the United States for possible
medical treatment.
   ``They say her only hope is in the United States,'' said Mrs.
Rosola on Saturday.
   The teen-ager and her mother are expected to arrive in Phoenix on
Monday and Miss Hlebkyna is scheduled for an examination at the
Arizona Heart Institute in Phoenix later in the week.
   Mrs. Rosola's efforts to bring her grandniece to the United
States ran into dead ends until she spoke with Theresa Gray,
director of acute intervention and transplant services at the heart
institute.
   ``From that time five months ago, Miss Gray was my angel,'' Mrs.
Rosola said. ``She was the mother of this case. Without her, I can
do nothing.''
   Gray set up an appointment with doctors, who agreed to examine
Miss Hlebkyna. She also contacted the office of Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz, whose staff enlisted the aid of the State Department.
   Mrs. Rosola, 66, has not seen her parents or only sister since
Germans invaded her Ukrainian village almost 45 years ago. She came
to the United States in 1955 and re-established contact with her
family in the Ukraine.
   Last month, Mrs. Rosola spoke to her family for the first time in
45 years.
   ``Her grandniece had a request that she would like to see America
before she dies and that maybe the American doctors can help her,''
Gray said.
   ``We're so thrilled that this is happening and that her wish will
come true.''
</TEXT>
