<FIRST>u i AM-Shultz     01-15 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shultz,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shultz Calls on Soviets to Dismantle Jamming Facilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heading to the windup of a 35-nation
human rights conference, Secretary of State George P. Shultz called
on the Soviet Union Sunday to uproot its facilities for jamming
Western radio broadcasts.
   The Soviets and their East European allies stopped jamming Radio
Liberty and Radio Free Europe late last year, and Shultz said
generally their societies were now ``more open.''
   He told reporters aboard the U.S. Air Force jet that carried him
to Vienna for his last diplomatic mission that ``I think we have
seen deeds.''
   But, Shultz said before a refueling stop here, ``What we now will
be pushing for and insisting on is a continuation of these deeds.''
In Vienna, Shultz will participate with foreign ministers of 34
other countries in the conclusion of a 27-month review of the
Helsinki agreement.
   Signed by the United States, Canada, the Soviet Union and 32
European countries in 1975, it called for a reduction of East-West
tensions and a broader exchange of people and ideas.
   ``In Helsinki,'' Shultz said, ``The diplomacy was way ahead of
the reality. Gradually, the reality has moved toward what we set out
as the objective. It has a long way to go, but we now have a process
of movement.''
   Shultz, who will leave office Friday with the end of the Reagan
administration, seemed confident the incoming Bush administration
would keep pressure on Moscow.
   ``We will keep attention on this subject continuously,'' he said.
   For his part, Shultz called on the Soviets to dismantle the giant
transmitters used to jam Western radio broadcasts and to tear down
the Berlin Wall.
   ``We think the practice by which you jam should be dismantled so
you can't start it up again,'' he told a half-dozen reporters taking
this final trip with him.
   Shultz called the concrete and barbed-wire wall which surrounds
West Berlin, keeping East Germans from fleeing, the ``acid test'' in
the human rights area.
   ``Until that wall comes down, it's just there,'' Shultz said.
``And it is more than a symbol. It tells you, by its very presence,
that you still have a long way to go.''
   Shultz seemed taken aback by published reports that the new
administration of President-elect Bush questioned a decision to hold
a human rights conference in Moscow in 1991.
   The decision was taken by President Reagan on Shultz's
recommendation. It was based on several steps taken by the Soviets,
including the release of more than 600 political prisoners, the
reunification of more than 100 families and increased Jewish
emigration.
   ``I certainly haven't heard a word from anyone in the Bush
administration,'' he said. ``It's obviously a question of some
judgment...''
   He said that by setting conditions for the Soviets, including
free access by all citizens to the conference, ``we managed to help
along the process quite a bit.''
   Shultz said that he had frequent foreign sessions with his
designated successor, James A. Baker III, including a two and
one-half hour meeting Saturday at Baker's home where the incoming
secretary of state is recuperating from the flu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
