<FIRST>u i AM-Jamaica     01-15 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jamaica,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seaga Sets Date for Jamaica Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Edward Seaga announced a
parliamentary election for Feb. 9 and criticized his main rival,
socialist opposition leader Michael Manley.
   Seaga said he ordered the shortest campaign period allowed under
Jamaican law. Business leaders urged a short campaign to minimize
the risk of unrest during the height of the winter tourist season.
   Seaga, 58, the Reagan administration's closest ally in the
Caribbean, is seeking an unprecedented third consecutive four-year
term.
   In a speech at a rally in Kingston, Seaga berated Manley's record
as a socialist and took credit for restoring political stability,
economic recovery and international relations.
   ``It is time for us to settle our future,'' he told the thousands
gathered at the televised rally. ``The issues are clear and the time
is here.''
   Critics say Seaga's economic restructuring and austerity measures
have neglected social services such as health and education, and his
popularity has continued to fade.
   Opinion polls have put Seaga's party roughly 13 points behind the
opposition for the past two years. Seaga narrowed the gap slightly
shortly after Hurricane Gilbert struck, but has since fallen back.
   The tourist industry, Jamaica's main foreign-exchange earner, is
still reeling from Hurricane Gilbert, which battered the island
Sept. 12.
   It will be Jamaica's first contested general election since 1980,
when more than 700 people were killed in street skirmishes during a
nine-month campaign. Manley and his leftist People's National Party
boycotted the last election in 1983 in a dispute over voter
registration. The boycott left Seaga's center-right Jamaican Labor
Party with all 60 seats in Parliament.
   Manley, 64, who as prime minister during the 1970s forged close
relations with Cuba, alarming the United States and foreign
investors, has been calling for a new election ever since.
   Jamaica, a nation of 2.3 million people 90 miles south of Cuba,
gained independence from Britain in 1962.
</TEXT>
