<FIRST>u i AM-China-Vietnam     01-15 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Vietnam,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>China and Vietnam Open Talks on Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China on Monday acknowledged that a senior
Vietnamese official was in Beijing for talks on Cambodia, the issue
that for the past decade has deeply divided the two socialist
neighbors.
   China in the past has said it would not hold direct talks with
Hanoi until Vietnam removes its troops fighting China-backed
resistance forces in Cambodia.
   ``First Deputy Foreign Minister of Vietnam Dinh Nho Liem arrived
in Beijing on Jan. 14 for private consultations with Chinese Vice
Foreign Minister Liu Shuqing on a political settlement of the
(Cambodian) question,'' the Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
   Eastern European sources said Liem's visit, the first by a
high-ranking Vietnamese official in more than nine years, could pave
the way for a meeting between China's Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
and his Vietnamese counterpart, Nguyen Co Thach.
   The Vietnamese Embassy in Beijing would say only that Liem will
be talking about bilateral relations and matters of mutual concern.
   Liem's arrival Saturday night was not reported by the Chinese
media and his welcoming venue was changed to Beijing's old airport,
which is used for high-level diplomatic visits, in an apparent
effort to evade foreign journalists who had learned he was on a
commercial flight from Bangkok.
   Relations between Beijing and Hanoi crumbled after Vietnam's
late-1978 invasion of Cambodia to drive the pro-Chinese Khmer Rouge
from power. China launched a 20-day border war against Vietnam in
1979 to ``punish'' the Vietnamese for its military actions in
Cambodia.
   China is the main arms supplier to the Khmer Rouge and other
resistance groups in Cambodia.
   Foreign Minister Qian, in a news conference in Paris Saturday,
repeated China's stand that Cambodia is the major obstacle blocking
improved relations with Vietnam and said Vietnam must take the
initiative by withdrawing its troops as soon as possible.
   However, in recent months China has taken a more conciliatory
stand on some aspects of the Cambodian conflict in an apparent
effort to expedite the peace process.
   In August, China opened direct talks with the Soviet Union,
Vietnam's main financial supporter, on Cambodia, and now says enough
progress has been made to hold the first Chinese-Soviet summit in 30
years.
   Previously, China said Moscow's backing of Vietnam's occupation
of Cambodia was the main obstacle to normalization of Chinese-Soviet
relations.
   China also has given assurances that it does not support the
return to power of the Khmer Rouge, blamed for the deaths of 1
million Cambodians during their brutal 1975-78 rule. It has said it
is willing to reduce its assistance to the Khmer Rouge and other
guerrilla forces as Vietnam pulls out.
   China has called for the formation of a coalition government
headed by resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk and including
the Vietnam-backed Heng Samrin faction.
   Sihanouk's son, Prince Ranariddh, said last week that China had
agreed to hold direct talks with Vietnam at the urging of the Soviet
Union, which says it favors an early settlement in Cambodia,
including a Vietnamese pullout.
   Vietnam claims it has about 50,000 troops in Cambodia and has set
a target of September for total withdrawal. China says previous
Vietnamese withdrawals were mere troop rotations but has said the
setting of the September target date was a ``step forward.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890115-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-15-89 2317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PoliceSting     01-15 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Police Sting,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Activist Claims Police Abuse in Long Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil rights activist who arranged a
sting operation to prove local police harass blacks charged Sunday
an officer beat him and pushed his head through a glass window
during a routine traffic stop.
   Police disputed the charge, but said they would investigate it.
   Don Jackson, a Hawthorne police sergeant on administrative leave,
said that he and the driver of the car he was in didn't do anything
illegal to provoke police when stopped Saturday night. Jackson said
he has a sore back, but no cuts, from the incident.
   The traffic stop was secretly recorded by a KNBC-TV news crew and
was scheduled to be broadcast on NBC's ``The Today Show'' on Monday,
according to KNBC.
   The tape, segments of which were broadcast on Sunday news shows,
showed an officer using profanity during a verbal exchange with
Jackson and a storefront window breaking around Jackson when the
officer searched him for weapons.
   ``You merely have to be black in the wrong neighborhood; or even
it's the right neighborhood,'' Jackson said in a news conference
Sunday. ``We were there five minutes. We had just gotten off the
freeway.''
   He said that he arranged the sting ``fully in commemoration of
the efforts of Martin Luther King,'' Jackson said. ``That really is
what gave me the courage to do this.'' The slain civil rights leader
would have been 60 on Sunday.
   Jackson, who belongs to a group called Police Misconduct Lawyer
Referral Service, said he was told police frequent a strip of the
Pacific Coast Highway in this city 20 miles south of Los Angeles.
   About 11:30 p.m. Saturday, Jackson and a friend were driving in
that area at Martin Luther King Boulevard when police stopped their
car, claiming that it was straddling lanes, said Jackson, 30, who
was a passenger in the vehicle driven by an off-duty corrections
officer.
   Jackson alleged that Officer Mark Dickey slammed his head through
the window and painfully pulled one of his fingers back.
   ``Next, he took me to the back of the car and slammed my head
into the trunk of the car,'' Jackson alleged, ``(Then) he ordered me
to spread my feet out. He kicked my legs as hard as he could.''
   Authorities deny that Dickey pushed Jackson's head through the
storefront but are investigating the allegations, said Lt. Mike Hill.
   ``We're going to conduct a complete and thorough investigation,''
he said.
   Police booked Jackson for investigation of interfering with
police and challenging a police officer. They set his bail at
$12,000, then reduced it to $250 and finally released Jackson on his
own recognizance more than six hours later.
   He said he plans to file a personnel action with police against
Dickey and a lawsuit against the department.
   David Lynn of the lawyer referral service said Long Beach
residents have filed 50 misconduct complaints against city police
officers. Of those, 27 were filed by black people and 24 of those
cases involved white police officers, he said.
   Jackson was involved in a similar sting last February at an
upscale shopping area in Los Angeles, where he was arrested after
allegedly refusing an officer's request to move along.
</TEXT>
