<FIRST>r a AM-TridentArrival     01-15 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trident Arrival,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>USS Tennessee Hailed as Instrument of Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. MARYS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS Tennessee, the first of 10 Trident
missile -firing submarines that will operate from a south Georgia
base, was hailed at an arrival ceremony Sunday as an instrument of
peace.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee,
said the survivability of ballistic missile submarines make them an
essential part of the nation's nuclear deterrent force.
   Because the vessels operate deep in the ocean in relative safety,
leaders would have more time to assess their actions in a crisis,
said Nunn, D-Ga.
   ``It helps us prevent war by accident and helps us preserve
peace,'' said Nunn. ``They don't have to squeeze that nuclear
trigger.''
   The ceremony was held on a wharf at the Kings Bay Naval Submarine
Base with about 800 guests, including Navy Secretary William Ball
III, U.S. Sen. Wyche Fowler of Georgia and U.S. Rep. Lindsay Thomas,
whose district includes Kings Bay. Thomas and Fowler are both
Democrats.
   Ball, who has served in the Reagan administration since February,
described the Tennessee as the most significant weapons development
since the advent of Polaris submarines in 1960.
   ``In a very uncertain world of Gadhafis and Khomeinis, and very
unpredictable communist leaders, this is a necessary instrument on
behalf of the national security of our country and the free world,''
Fowler said.
   While the dignitaries spoke, about 100 anti-nuclear weapons
protesters demonstrated at the front gate. Navy officials said nine
protesters were arrested, including one in Florida for apparently
trying to swim toward the approaching submarine.
   The Metanoia Community, which coordinated the protest, said up to
24 peace groups would be represented during the demonstrations.
   Nunn said he respected the views of the protesters, but said that
``those in uniform are also dedicated to the cause of peace.''
   The Tennessee, an Ohio-class submarine commissioned Dec. 17 in
New London, Conn., is designed to fire the Navy's new Trident II
missiles. The missiles have a range of 6,000 miles and each has up
to 10 warheads.
   The missile has been undergoing land launching tests at Cape
Canaveral, Fla. The Tennessee will be used for the first sea
launches of the new missile.
   Tridents are the Navy's largest and most powerful submarines.
They are 560 feet long and displace 18,700 tons. Each is equipped
with 24 missiles and staffed with a crew of 157 men.
   With a Navy band playing ``Anchors Away'' and gulls and pelicans
flying overhead, the Tennessee was nudged into position along a
wharf by three tugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
