<FIRST>r i AM-Angola-Cubans     01-15 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-Cubans,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>First 3,000 Cuban Troops Out of Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet ship left Angola Sunday with 975
Cuban troops, meeting a first-stage deadline for Cuba to pull out
3,000 troops under terms of a tripartite agreement, the Portuguese
news agency LUSA reported.
   The ship Leonid Sovinov steamed out of the port city of Luanda
with the troops, the news agency reported in a dispatch from Luanda.
   The Cuban troop withdrawal began Jan. 10 and is to continue
through mid-1991 by which time an estimated 50,000 troops are to
have returned to the Caribbean island nation.
   Cuba, Angola and South Africa signed an agreement Dec. 22 in
which South Africa agreed to grant independence to Namibia in return
for withdrawal of the Cubans who first arrived in Angola in 1975
following a South African incursion into the southern African nation.
   All South African troops withdrew from Angola following an Aug. 8
cease-fire. A 10-nation U.N. military observer group is monitoring
the Cuban withdrawal.
</TEXT>
