<NOTE>Robert Lekachman</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Lekachman, an economist who taught at
several American universities and wrote two books critical of the
Reagan administration, died Saturday of cancer. He was 68.
   Two of his books on economics, ``The Age of Keynes,'' published
in 1966, and ``A History of Economic Ideas,'' published in 1959,
have been translated into several languages.
   He also wrote two books critical of the Reagan administration:
``Visions and Nightmares: America after Reagan,'' published in 1987,
and ``Greed is not enough: Reaganomics,'' published in 1982.
   A frequent lecturer, Lekachman taught at Barnard College from
1948 to 1965, then joined the State University of New York at
Stonybrook, where he became chairman of the Economics Department. He
joined the faculty at Lehman in 1973.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Hiroshi Yabuta</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hiroshi Yabuta, the first Japanese to receive a
liver transplant in another country, died Friday of acute kidney
failure. He was 53.
   No liver or heart transplants have been performed in Japan since
1968 because of controversy over the legal definition of death for
potential organ donors. Yabuta received the transplant at
Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston on April 8, 1985, and
returned home seven months later.
   Kyodo News Service said an autopsy showed no irregularities in
Yabuta's transplanted liver or any symptoms of rejection, and his
death may have been caused anti-rejection drugs lowering his body's
resistance.
   Since Yabuta's transplant about 30 Japanese, mostly children,
have received liver transplants in the United States, Europe and
Australia. Eight of them have died, Kyodo said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Fritz Hartman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fritz Albert Hartman, speaker for the Truk state
legislature in the Federated States of Micronesia, died Sunday
during a plane flight from Guam to Honolulu after suffering a brain
hemorrhage. He was 46.
   Hartman, who was elected speaker in March 1988, collapsed in Truk
on Friday and spent two days in Guam Memorial Hospital in Agana,
Guam, before departing for Honlulu accompanied by a doctor and
nurse, a hospital supervisor said.
   Hartman had also held the speaker's post in Truk's legislature in
1986.
   The Federated States of Micronesia is about 3,000 miles southwest
of Hawaii.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ernie Blake</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ernie Blake, founder of the Taos Ski
Valley resort, died Saturday of double pneumonia at an Albuquerque
hospital. He was 75.
   Blake, born Ernest Bloch in Germany in March, 1913, grew up near
the Swiss ski resort of St. Moritz, and began skiing at age 4. In
1938 he came to the United States and served in U.S. military
intelligence in World War II.
   In Germany, Blake helped interrogate Nazi leaders Hermann
Goering, Albert Speer and others during the war crimes trials at
Nuremberg.
   He was inducted into the U.S. Ski Hall of Fame in Ishpeming,
Mich., in February, 1987, for his contributions to skiing.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Norris</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. John Norris, a leader in the fight
against alcoholism for 50 years, died Friday of congestive heart
failure. He was 85.
   Norris, who headed the Alcoholics Anonymous General Service Board
through the 1960s and 70s, pioneered the idea of dealing with
alcoholics at work.
   Norris was associate medical director, then medical director of
Eastman Kodak Co. from the 1930s until his retirement in 1969. A
non-alcoholic, he was an Alcoholic's Anonymous board member from
1951 to 1978.
</TEXT>
