<FILEID>AP-NR-01-15-89 1337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-SickCity Bjt   01-15 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Sick City, Bjt,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Firms Cut Jobs Amid Sluggish Volume, Low Stock Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City, London's equivalent of Wall Street, is
suffering another wave of cutbacks, reflecting persistently sluggish
trading, low stock prices and smaller profits at brokerages.
   Further cuts are expected in coming months, and weaker firms have
become targets of takeover speculation.
   The retrenchment, the third in two years, has dented many
investment firms' ambitious plans of becoming powerful global
traders.
   It also has crimped Britain's flamboyant new breed of yuppies,
who came to symbolize Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's capitalist
revolution with flashy sports cars, swanks suits and champagne.
   The investment firms are suffering from the intense competition
following Big Bang, the 1986 deregulation of Britain's financial
markets which attracted new international players. The firms also
have been clobbered by the October 1987 stock market crash, which
scared many investors.
   Their margins have narrowed sharply and few, if any, are believed
to be making money.
   Analysts estimate that between 1,000 and 3,000 jobs have been cut
in the recent wave, bringing the number of cuts since Big Bang to an
estimated 10,000. Estimates of the number of employees in the City
range from 250,000 to 450,000.
   Although not unexpected, the recent cuts still were a nasty shock.
   ``There were the sob stories and the hard luck stories,'' said
Simon Coombe, a banking analyst at the London investment firm UBS
Phillips and Drew.
   He added that for sacked traders hunting new jobs, ``the most
important thing now is not the salary being offered but the length
of contract being offered. Security is very obviously more on
people's minds these days.''
   The first wave of cuts came soon after Big Bang, when the firms
quickly realized there were too many players chasing too little
money. The second followed the crash, and the third was prompted by
the firms' usual yearend review of results.
   ``It's the time of year that people look back at the numbers they
made in the previous year and look ahead at their budget,'' Coombe
said. ``1988 was a year that most securities firms didn't make a lot
of money. 1989 doesn't look all that much better,''
   Big increases in British interest rates in the second half of
1988 have also hurt the stock market, said banking analyst Chris
Smith of Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd.
   Some firms have pulled out of market-making in equities or
British government bonds, called gilts, or both. Or they have cut
back the number of equities in which they make markets.
   The gilts market also has been hurt by the Conservative
goverment's tight fiscal spending policy. Britain is enjoying a rare
budget surplus and the government is repaying debt.
   Market-makers are the specialist brokers who continuously quote
prices in certain stocks on the London market's computerized trading
system.
   ``People are trying to improve their profitability,'' Coombe
said. ``One of the ways to improve profitability when revenue is not
going to increase is to cut costs.''
   Morgan Grenfell PLC made the biggest cuts in the recent wave when
it withdrew from market-making in equities and gilts, slashing 450
of its 3,000 jobs in December.
   The firm said it lost $40.3 million in the first 11 months of the
year from such trading.
   Ironically, market-making was an activity the traders had sought
and won under Big Bang. Previously it was restricted to 17 special
firms called jobbers.
   The number of market-makers soared to 61 after Big Bang, and
since has receded to 51.
   The average daily value of equities trading on London's Stock
Exchange stood at $3.1 billion in November, well below a July 1987
peak of $5.4 billion.
   Big Bang, which occurred in October 1986, also abolished minimum
commissions, allowed banks to enter the securities business and
permitted foreign firms to join London's Stock Exchange.
   The exchange introduced computer systems allowing dealers to
trade off the stock exchange floor using phones and screens.
   American firms, which had geared up especially aggressively for
Big Bang, also have cut back.
   Among them, Security Pacific Corp.'s London unit announced early
in January it was pulling out of market-making in gilts and
Eurobonds, cutting 135 of its 1,400 London jobs. Chase Manhattan
Bank N.A. said it was withdrawing from market-making in British
equities, cutting 135 of 2,500 British-based jobs.
   Japanese firms had proceeded more cautiously, and haven't
publicly announced any massive layoffs.
   The number of major trading firms in London is expected to shrink
over the next few years, from more than two dozen now to three or
four, with smaller participants establishing niches.
   ``The most widely held belief is, as old Darwin said, the fittest
will survive,'' Coombe said.
</TEXT>
