<FIRST>r f AM-ConceptCars     01-15 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Concept Cars,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Concept Cars: Lots Of Looks For The Dream Set</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ada Maxwell stood next to the Chrysler Millennium,
wondering if an alien should be at the wheel.
   ``It looks like it came from outer space,'' the Detroit woman
said, shaking her head.
   The Milennium, one of more than a dozen concept cars, was
displayed at the North American International Auto Show, which
closed Sunday in Detroit. The hand-built, one-of-kind vehicles drew
skeptical glances from some show-goers and more studied appraisals
from others.
   Chrysler Corp. bills the Millennium as its ``safetyr automobiles on
the road, it has air bags, anti-lock brakes and
a heated windshield.
   But it has some other things, too, that aren't on the road,
including voice-activated controls, infrared beams to pick out
objects in front of the car in the dark of night and collision
warning radar _ some of the stuff on today's jet planes.
   ``That's a test-bed kind of car,'' Chrysler spokesman Ben Dunn
said. ``That car as it sits would never reach production, but
elements of it would.''
   Ever since car makers had design studios, there have been concept
or dream cars. It's one way to test ideas on the public.
   Recent technology has made assembly lines more flexible, making
it possible for engineering, manufacturing and other car-making
experts to become involved early in the design process. That has
resulted in concept cars taking on a decidedly road worthy and
marketable look.
   One of the concept cars close to production is the Buick Park
Avenue Essence. Gill Davenport, a project coordinator for the
Essence, said a version of it could be ready for the road in the
1993 or 1994 model year.
   ``Mainly, this car was put together to give people a feeling that
this was an extension of home,'' he said while standing next to the
shiny, aquamarine car.
   Some homey touches include a super-thin, 5-inch color television
set dropping down from the roof for rear-seat passengers and
separate sound systems with headphones for each of the passengers.
   ``It's fantastic, the color, the style,'' said Thelma Paulausky
of Taylor, a Buick owner who said she'd like to have an Essence.
   Other concept cars at the show, while unique, aren't nearly as
close to making it to the road as is the Essence.
   The Ford Splash and the Plymouth Speedster are tiny two-seaters
with a decidedly southern California look. Seats are covered in
neoprene, the same material used in wet suits.
   ``I could just see a zillion of them in California,'' Betty
Schreiber of Detroit said of the Speedster. She said she like
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Oay and iridescent</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   green.
   ``It looks like a Lego toy,'' Mike Krol of Detroit said while
standing next to her and the Speedster display.
   Over at the Ford truck exhibit, where the Splash was displayed,
model Leah Murray said people asked frequently about the car's
suspension and its upholstery.
   ``It looks like it can go under water,'' said Murray, costumed in
a wet suit. ``They always ask if it's in production and when it will
be coming out.''
   Like Plymouth, Ford has not announced plans to produce the car.
   The Dodge Viper R-T 10 is a concept car that has a familiar look
to sports car enthusiasts. To some, like John Koss of Rochester, it
has lines similar to the Shelby Cobra.
   Unlike many concept cars, the interior of the Viper is spartan.
There is no TV, no elaborate sound system or separate climate
controls. Dials and gauges are reminiscent of roadsters 25 years old.
   ``This is getting back to basics,'' said Koss, looking over the
fire-engine red car with chromed exhaust pipes running along the
rocker panels under the doors.
   Jazzy styling common to concept cars certainly isn't lost on the
luxury end of the market. Displayed beside traditional Sedan De
Villes and Fleetwoods, is the Cadillac Solitare, a deep burgundy
number that got its share of attention at the show.
   The classic Cadillac front end, with the well-known crest, is
gone from the Solitare, something that disappointed Wally Mazer of
Westland, Mich.
   ``They're going out of their class,'' he said. When asked if he
could see himself behind the wheel of a Solitare, Mazer said without
hesitating:
   ``Oh no, I'm retired.''
</TEXT>
