<FIRST>r f AM-BostonCo.     01-15 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boston Co.,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Co. Reports Overstatement of Profits By $30 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston Co.'s profits for the first three quarters
of 1988 were overstated by $30 million, more than twice as high as
preliminary estimates, officials with the investment firm said.
   A spokesman for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., Boston Co.'s parent
firm, said Friday a committee of outside auditors and Shearson
officers arrived at the higher estimate after an examination of
Boston's financial position.
   The spokesman Thomas Schick, said the committee was trying to
determine who was responsible for the overstatement and probably
would reach a decision within a few weeks.
   ``At the moment, no conclusions have been reached as regards
assignment of responsibility, and as a result there is no decision
on personnel matters,'' Schick said.
   Three top Boston Co. officers were suspended last month
discrepancies in the investment firm's financial reports.
   Shearson declined to name the three officers, who were suspended
with pay when the overstatement was disclosed. They have been
identified by newspapers as President James N. von Germeten,
Executive Vice President Joseph F. Murphy and Chief Financial
Officer Michael J. Walsh.
   Shick said the overstatement involved no misuse of company or
client funds, and, ``we do not believe that any laws were broken.''
   He said the overstatement resulted primarily from deferred
booking of expenses and, to a lesser extent, accelerated or early
recording of revenue.
   ``The review's conclusion was that what was involved here was
accounting decisions that would boost the reported earnings,'' he
said. ``In terms of what the motive was, I cannot possibly speak to
that.''
   Shick said the overstatement was $44 million in pre-tax or $30
million in post-tax income. He said Shearson would not divulge the
company's actual earnings, but that Boston Co. would be profitable
in the fourth quarter and, for the full year, would achieve the
third highest earnings level in its history.
   Boston Co. is the parent company of Boston Safe Deposit &amp; Trust
Co., the nation's 17th largest bank, with more than $11 billion in
deposits.
   The company also runs a family of mutual funds and is a major
manager of pension funds. It has a total of about $35 billion in
assets under management.
</TEXT>
