<FILEID>AP-NR-01-15-89 1623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PrimeComputer     01-15 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall Street Now Betting Prime Computer Will Be Taken Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MAI Basic Four, the small California computer
company bidding to take over much larger Prime Computer Inc. for
$970 million, has overcome initial skepticism on Wall Street and is
now considered by securities analysts and arbitrageurs to have an
excellent chance of success.
   Despite court battles that still could block the tender offer,
some securities analysts say the game is over.
   ``It would appear to be a done deal, which is what the arbitrage
community has been saying by bidding up the price of the stock,''
Robert Herwick, who follows Prime for Hambrecht &amp; Quist, said
Friday. ``These folks at MAI have done the unbelievable.''
   When Tustin, Calif.-based MAI Basic, controlled by New York
investor Bennett S. LeBow, launched the $20-per-share offer on Nov.
15, many Wall Street professionals did not take it seriously.
   Underlying the early skepticism was uncertainty about the
strength of LeBow's investment banker, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
which was under investigation in the Wall Street insider trading
scandal.
   In addition, disclosure filings that accompanied the bid said MAI
Basic had previously offered to sell itself to Prime, which had
shown little interest.
   ``When (MAI Basic) turned around and made the offer to buy Prime,
initially everyone just thought it was a backdoor way of trying to
sell itself, and they just laughed,'' said one New York arbitrageur,
who declined to be quoted by name.
   But MAI pursued the bid vigorously, and Drexel Burnham Lambert
moved last month to settle the allegations against it by pleading
guilty to six unspecified felonies and paying a record $650 million
fine.
   ``Now the general feeling is Drexel is going to come back roaring
and try to prove its mettle,'' said the arbitrageur. ``It's really
Drexel's desire to come back from all that confusion that makes this
deal credible.''
   Stockholders also have been effectively casting ballots for the
offer by tendering their shares of Prime, which is headquartered in
Natick and has more than 12,000 employees worldwide.
   MAI Basic said Thursday that 29.3 million shares have been
tendered so far. Added to the 1.9 million shares that MAI and its
affiliate, Brooke Partners, already hold, that represents 64.8
percent of Prime's outstanding common stock.
   Prime officials were quick to point out, however, that
convertible debentures _ interest-bearing bonds that the owner can
convert to common stock _ could create several million more shares.
If that happens, MAI Basic would have less than 50 percent of
Prime's stock.
   The tender offer is conditioned on MAI Basic's obtaining at least
67 percent of the stock. Prime stock closed at $19.12{ a share
Friday in New York Stock Exchange Composite trading.
   MAI Basic also faces two major obstacles: a stockholder rights
plan, or ``poison pill,'' that is the subject of a Delaware court
battle; and a temporary injunction imposed by a Massachusetts judge.
   The poison pill, a defense against hostile takeovers, would
further increase the number of shares outstanding, making a takeover
prohibitively costly. The injunction bars MAI Basic from pursuing
its bid until it has made full disclosure of its financing
arrangements with Drexel Burnham Lambert.
   Despite the injunction, stockholders can still tender their
shares to a custodian. But until Judge A. David Mazzone rules that
MAI has made a full disclosure, MAI Basic cannot actually take
possession of the shares.
   Prime spokesman Richard Eckel said the combination of the poison
pill and the temporary injunction mean that ``a takeover is far from
a done deal.''
   Jay Stevens, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds, said Eckel was
legally correct.
   But, he said, ``a lot of us do feel it's getting close.''
</TEXT>
