<FILEID>AP-NR-01-15-89 1915EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Brazil-Economy 1stLd-Writethru   01-15 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Overhauls Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with union comment, detail of
wage freeze; picks up 8th graf pvs: The program...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Sunday imposed a
wage-and-price freeze, revamped the currency and laid off 60,000
public employees as part of a sweeping program to control soaring
inflation and trim a huge budget deficit.
   Union leaders immediately threatened to call for a nationwide
general strike to protest the measures, which eliminated an
automatic monthly indexing of wages to inflation.
   ``Inflation should fall drastically and abruptly,'' Finance
Minister Mailson da Nobrega said at a press conference Sunday.
Nobrega said the measures were the ``toughest'' a Brazilian
government has taken at any one time.
   Monday and Tuesday were declared bank holidays to allow time for
the financial system to adapt to the new measures, which included a
17 percent devaluation of the Cruzado, creation of the so-called
``new cruzado'' worth 1,000 old ones.
   It also scraps the automatic monthly indexing of contracts,
savings accounts, and most financial tranactions to cost of living
increases.
   Among the measures designed to slash the massive public spending
deficit were the layoff of about 60,000 civil servants' jobs, the
elimination of five Cabinet ministries and the closing of 42 state
companies and organs.
   The reform package put together by President Jose Sarney and his
economic advisors also includes a 45-day price freeze on about 200
basic commodities.
   Union leaders criticized the elimination of the wage index that
gives workers monthly wage increases. Union figures show that in the
past two years, workers' purchasing power has dipped in real terms
by about 40 percent because of losses to inflation.
   Under the new measures, workers will receive a last monthly
increase in January. In February, wages will be adjusted according
to the average inflation over the past 12 months and then frozen for
an indefinite period.
   ``We weren't consulted about the measures, which will cut into
worker's salaries,'' Luiz Mederos leader of the Sao Paulo metal
workers' union said. ``I have no doubts furious workers will react
negatively and they will have our support in organizing a nationwide
strike.''
   The program is the fourth anti-inflation plan since Sarney,
Brazil's first civilian president after 21 years of military rule,
took office in 1985.
   Brazil's inflation rate hit an all-time-high annual rate of 933
percent in 1988, substantially higher than 1987's 366 percent.
Inflation in December rose to 28.8 percent, well above the
25-percent limit set by business, social and government leaders in a
``social pact'' announced in November.
   Brazil's public sector deficit, widely believed to fuel
inflation, is running at about 6 percent of the nation's $300
billion gross national product.
   In addition, the country's economy is stagnating, with the gross
national product up just 0.04 percent in 1988, according to
government figures.
   Brazil is the Third World's leading debtor nation, owing $115
billion, or more than a third of its GNP, according to government
figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
